We learn from Marcus Varro that Mezentius‚king of Etruria, gave help to the Rutuli against the Latins at the price of receiving all the wine then in the territory of Latium. At Rome women were not allowed to drink wine. Among various instances we find that the wife of Egnatius Maetennus was clubbed to death by her husband for drinking wine from the vat, and that Romulus acquitted him on the charge of murder. Judge Gnaeus Domitius once gave a ver- dict that a certain woman appeared to have drunk more wine that was required for the sake of her health without her husband’s knowledge, and he fined her the amount of her dowry.
